uw.edu : privacy and why it matters
  https://it.uw.edu/guides/privacy/reference-materials/privacy-and-why-it-matters/

    types of privacy:
        intellectual, informational, bodily, communication, territorial

    types of privacy harms: 
        two categories: subjective and objective

        types:
	    physical, economic, discrimination, psychological, autonomy,
	    reputational, relationship

    reference: 
        personal data, classification, and structures - taxonomy and high-risk processing
	privacy principles, policy, laws, ethical considerations
        privacy by design framework

  privacy by design framework
  https://it.uw.edu/guides/privacy/take-action/design-for-privacy/

    step 1: review privacy principles
    step 2: learn about the privacy by design framework
              https://iapp.org/media/pdf/resource_center/pbd_implement_7found_principles.pdf
    step 3: refer to the take action menu to begin incorporating privacy by design

    reference: the development of the privacy by design framework is credited to 
               Ann Kavoukian, the former Information and Privacy Commissioner for Ontario

design for privacy
  https://it.uw.edu/guides/privacy/take-action/design-for-privacy/

    uw values: respect, integrity, diversity, excellence, collaboration, innovation
    uw principles: minization, accountability, protection, awareness


privacy by design
https://iapp.org/resources/article/oipc-privacy-by-design-resources/


pdf: privacy by design - the 7 foundational principles - 
       implementation and mapping of fair information practice              
       by Ann Cavoukian, www.privacybydesign.ca
https://iapp.org/media/pdf/resource_center/pbd_implement_7found_principles.pdf

    principles
        Proactive not Reactive; Preventative not Remedial
	Privacy as the Default Setting
	Privacy Embedded into Design
	Full Functionality – Positive-Sum, not Zero-Sum
	End-to-End Security – Full Lifecycle Protection
	Visibility and Transparency – Keep it Open
	Respect for User Privacy – Keep it User-Centric


